---
// Timestamp Decoder — a comprehensive, bidirectional converter across every
// timestamp/epoch format an analyst is likely to meet in DFIR work (Unix,
// Windows FILETIME, WebKit/Chrome, Mac Absolute Time, .NET Ticks, UUID v1,
// GPS, TAI64, and the common text/log formats), plus a reference table
// covering formats the live converter doesn't have its own field for (same
// "recipe builder + operator reference" page shape as the OSINT Crock Pot).
// Static page — prerender to HTML served from the CDN.
export const prerender = true;
import { css } from 'styled-system/css';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import TimestampConverter from '../../components/TimestampConverter.astro';
import { TIMESTAMP_FORMAT_REFERENCE } from '../../data/timestampFormats';

const sectionH2 = css({
  display: 'flex',
  alignItems: 'center',
  gap: '0.6rem',
  fontSize: '1.3rem',
  fontWeight: 700,
  mt: '2.5rem',
  mb: '1rem',
  pt: '1.5rem',
  borderTop: '1px solid token(colors.border)',
  scrollMarginTop: '90px',
});
const refTable = css({ width: '100%', borderCollapse: 'collapse', fontSize: '0.85rem' });
const refTh = css({ textAlign: 'left', color: 'textMuted', fontFamily: 'sans', fontWeight: 600, fontSize: '0.72rem', textTransform: 'uppercase', letterSpacing: '0.06em', p: '0.5rem 0.7rem', borderBottom: '1px solid token(colors.border)' });
// Kept as a plain object (not a pre-atomized css() call) so refTdCode below
// can css(refTdBase, ...) — a deep object merge that deterministically
// overrides refTdBase's own color, unlike concatenating two independently-
// atomized class strings (see STYLE_GUIDE.md "Buttons" for the exact
// failure mode this avoids — this cell was previously composed as
// `${refTd} ${refCode}`, which left the winning color up to Panda's atomic-
// class ordering rather than the intended mono/primary styling).
const refTdBase = { p: '0.5rem 0.7rem', borderBottom: '1px solid token(colors.border)', color: 'text', verticalAlign: 'top' } as const;
const refTd = css(refTdBase);
const refTdMuted = css({ ...refTdBase, color: 'textMuted', fontSize: '0.8rem' });
const refTdCode = css(refTdBase, { fontFamily: 'mono', fontSize: '0.78rem', color: 'primary' });
const sectionText = css({ color: 'text', lineHeight: 1.7, fontSize: '0.95rem', mb: '1rem', '&:last-child': { mb: 0 } });
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Timestamp Decoder"
  description="A comprehensive, bidirectional timestamp/epoch converter for DFIR — Unix, Windows FILETIME, WebKit, Mac Absolute Time, .NET Ticks, UUID v1, GPS, TAI64, and common text/log date formats, all synced live."
>
  <PageHeader
    breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Tool Catalog', href: '/tools/' }, { label: 'Timestamp Decoder' }]}
    eyebrow="Time & Correlation"
    title="Timestamp Decoder"
    description="Every timestamp format an analyst actually runs into, kept in sync — edit any field and every other format updates from the same instant."
  />

  <aside
    class={css({
      bg: 'bgSubtle',
      border: '1px solid token(colors.border)',
      borderLeftWidth: '3px',
      borderLeftColor: 'primary',
      borderRadius: 'md',
      p: '1rem 1.25rem',
      mb: '1.5rem',
    })}
  >
    <p class={css({ color: 'text', lineHeight: 1.7, fontSize: '0.95rem', m: 0 })}>
      Different artifacts encode time completely differently — NTFS and the registry use{' '}
      <strong class={css({ color: 'text' })}>Windows FILETIME</strong>, Chrome's history DB uses a{' '}
      <strong class={css({ color: 'text' })}>WebKit timestamp</strong>, Safari/iOS use{' '}
      <strong class={css({ color: 'text' })}>Mac Absolute Time</strong>, and log lines show up in half a dozen
      text formats with or without a year, offset, or timezone at all. Getting the epoch/unit wrong silently
      shifts a timeline by hours, years, or centuries. Every constant below was independently researched and
      adversarially fact-checked against authoritative sources (Microsoft Learn, the relevant RFCs, Apple and
      forensic documentation) — see the reference table for citations and caveats. Two format families (FAT/
      DOS packed date-time and legacy BSD syslog) have no timezone or year field of their own; the zone
      picker below the instant boxes in the converter governs which zone those formats resolve against,
      defaulting to your browser's local zone when none is picked.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <h2 id="converter" class={css({ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: '0.6rem', fontSize: '1.3rem', fontWeight: 700, mb: '1rem', scrollMarginTop: '90px' })}>
    <Icon name="clock" size={20} class={css({ color: 'primary' })} /> Converter
  </h2>
  <TimestampConverter />

  <h2 id="reference" class={sectionH2}>
    <Icon name="list" size={20} class={css({ color: 'primary' })} /> Format reference
  </h2>
  <p class={css({ color: 'textMuted', fontSize: '0.85rem', mb: '1rem' })}>
    Every format the research covered — formats marked "live field above" are wired into the converter;
    the rest are either numerically identical to one that is, or too artifact-specific (bit-packed, split
    across multiple fields) for a practical single input.
  </p>
  <div class={css({ overflowX: 'auto' })}>
    <table class={refTable}>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class={refTh}>Format</th>
          <th class={refTh}>Epoch</th>
          <th class={refTh}>Unit</th>
          <th class={refTh}>Seen in DFIR</th>
          <th class={refTh}>Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          TIMESTAMP_FORMAT_REFERENCE.map((f) => (
            <tr>
              <td class={refTd}>
                <strong class={css({ color: 'text' })}>{f.name}</strong>
                {f.linkedFormatId && (
                  <div class={css({ fontSize: '0.72rem', color: 'accent', mt: '0.15rem' })}>live field above</div>
                )}
              </td>
              <td class={refTdCode}>{f.epochOrigin}</td>
              <td class={refTdMuted}>{f.unit}</td>
              <td class={refTdMuted}>{f.whereSeenInDFIR}</td>
              <td class={refTdMuted}>{f.note ?? ''}</td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 id="dst-and-correlation" class={sectionH2}>
    <Icon name="globe" size={20} class={css({ color: 'primary' })} /> Daylight saving time & timeline correlation
  </h2>
  <p class={sectionText}>
    Daylight saving time (DST) shifts a zone's clock forward, typically by one hour, for part of the
    year, then back again — and both transitions create a genuinely ambiguous window. During the
    fall-back transition, the same wall-clock hour occurs <em>twice</em> in one night, so a log entry
    reading e.g. "01:30" could be either occurrence, an hour apart, with nothing in the timestamp
    itself to tell you which. During the spring-forward transition, an entire hour of wall-clock time
    is skipped and never occurs at all — a timestamp that appears to fall inside it is simply wrong.
    Correlating a multi-source timeline across a DST boundary without accounting for this can silently
    shift events by an hour in either direction.
  </p>
  <p class={sectionText}>
    This converter always resolves a zone's offset using the runtime's real, current IANA tzdata rules
    for that specific zone <em>and</em> date — never a fixed or naive offset baked into the tool
    itself. That's why the Local and Converted boxes above recompute their offset every time the
    underlying instant changes, and why the same zone name can correctly show a different offset for a
    January timestamp than a July one; it's also what the "Daylight Saving Time" / "Standard Time"
    label next to each zone name reflects.
  </p>
  <p class={sectionText}>
    General guidance for working with dates and times in DFIR: prefer UTC as the common reference when
    correlating any multi-source timeline — it has no DST and no ambiguity. A source system's
    local-time log usually doesn't record which side of a DST transition it falls on, so don't assume
    one; verify a system's configured timezone, and whether that zone observes DST at all, before
    trusting its local timestamps at face value.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
